	<text>
		<body>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_stern_estera">Estera Stern</persName> Testimony (doc. 301/965)</p>

			<p>Typescript, 1 page, 210 x 295 mm, Polish language</p>

			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010965_01.jpg"/> The <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067784/porici.html"
					>Parschnitz</placeName><note type="gloss"><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067784/porici.html">Parschnitz -
						Pořiči</placeName>(the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3077311/czechia.html">Czech Lands</placeName>). In the text:
					Parssnitz.</note>
				<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067784/porici.html">camp</placeName> (the <placeName ref="#ehri_et_sudeten"
					>Sudeten</placeName>)</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_stern_estera">Estera Stern</persName>, born on <date when="1927-11-27">November 27, 1927</date>, in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3085128/sosnowiec.html">Sosnowiec</placeName>; parents: <persName ref="#ehri_et_stern_aron"
					>Aron</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_stern_majtla">Majtla née Skóra</persName>; before the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080">war</term>: a <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1214">student</term>.</p>
			<p>I was taken to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> from the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-683" type="ghetto">Sosnowiec ghetto</placeName> at <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/11668510/park-srodula.html">Środula</placeName> in <date when="1943-02">February 1943</date>.
				Thirty-three <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">girls</term>, including myself, were
				taken to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067784/porici.html">Parschnitz</placeName> (in the <placeName ref="#ehri_et_sudeten"
					>Sudeten</placeName>). When we arrived there we were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837"
					type="subject">barracked</term> in an old disused spinning <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>. 250 other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">girls</term> had been quartered there already. There
				were three large halls changed into three large rooms there. They were equipped with wooden bunk beds, cupboards and benches. At the
				beginning there were 300 of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">girls</term> there
				altogether, and we occupied the room on the ground floor and another one on the second floor. After some time, a year after my
				arrival, we were joined by a <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> of 600
					<term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> from <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName> and by about 600 <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825"
					type="subject">women</term>. They were given the room on the first floor, which had been empty before. At first our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> was surrounded with a fence only. Then,
				after a year, when the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> was taken over by
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> command, it was surrounded with
				barbed wire. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-482" type="subject">Lagerführerin</term> was a <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> woman named <persName ref="#ehri_et_hawlik_else"
					>Hawlik</persName>. At the beginning she treated us very decently and she took motherly care of us. But as it turned out later,
				her kindness was illusory and strictly calculated. She tried to convince us that as we were safe in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> under her care, we should write home and
				tell our people to send us valuables and jewellery which, as she argued, would be safer in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> than at home, from where our parents would
				be deported sooner or later. Most of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject"
					>girls</term> followed her advice. As it turned out later, she took advantage of our trust and confiscated everything. As we also
				learnt later, she was a member of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>.
				Thus, after the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> had been taken over by
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_hawlik_else"
					>Hawlik</persName> revealed her real face. She set specially trained dogs on us for the slightest offence. She robbed us of our
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">rations</term>, which shrank visibly because of
				that.</p>
			<p>We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in a textile <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3063907/trutnov.html">Tratenau</placeName>.<note place="bottom">Tratenau - Trutnov (the Czech
					Lands).</note>We had to cover 6 kilometres’ distance on foot to get to our <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> place. The way to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> was a hell, especially in winter. We left
				at 5 o’clock in the morning, groping in the mountains, up to our knees in the snow. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">girls</term> often took off their heavy wooden shoes,
				which were a burden on such a way, and they preferred to walk barefooted. They had to pay for their carelessness with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">pneumonia</term>, and sometimes with their life. The
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in the spinning <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>, where we operated the machines, required a lot of
				attention. A slightest mistake could end up in a disability. I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					type="subject">worked</term> in the hardest unit, the so-called <foreign xml:lang="de">Feinsal</foreign>.<note type="gloss"
					>Feinsal may mean a room (Ger.: Saal) in which they spinned fine (Ger.: fein) yarn.</note>My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> required special concentration. Our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">rations</term> were very scanty. One of the reasons
				was that <persName ref="#ehri_et_hawlik_else">Hawlik</persName>, who stole our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">rations</term>. Thus, before leaving for <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term>, we were given ½ litre of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> which was supposed to be our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">dinner</term> in the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>. Our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">breakfast</term> consisted of 12 decagrams of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> and bitter <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">coffee</term>. For <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">supper</term>, on the other hand, each of us got three
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> and a spoonful of sauce.</p>
			<p>We became witnesses of horrid events two weeks before the arrival of the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName>. <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">Transports</term> of Jews <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-623" type="subject">evacuated</term> from various <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camps</term> went past our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> on their way to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">Germany</placeName>. They had a few days’ break at the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term>, and that was followed by the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selection</term>. Those were emaciated <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569">hungry</term> and miserable people. They were so
				changed that it happened that a sister failed to recognise her brother. Those unfit to physical effort were finished off at our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> in front of our very eyes. The <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<foreign xml:lang="de"><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-478" type="subject">Aufseherinen</term></foreign>
				found the spectacle funny: they looked and smiled.</p>
			<p>The <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us on <date when="1945-08-05">May
					8</date> at 4 pm.</p>
			<p>Recorded by <persName ref="#ehri_et_landau_hedda">H. Landau</persName>.</p>
		</body>
